From f2f86cfd89c0d216d05c1d0e4dd1600f07873507 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vasu Bhatia <git@vbh.ai>
Date: Tue, 28 Apr 2026 13:32:32 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] display: use device brightness range for HBM controller, not
 PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MAX

When HighBrightnessModeController is constructed with the global
PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MIN/MAX (0.0/1.0), BrightnessRangeController
reports the HBM max as 1.0 even though DisplayDeviceConfig caps
mBacklightMaximum lower (e.g. 80/255 on the e-ink Minimal Phone).

The QS brightness slider then maps its full 0-100% physical range to
float 0-1.0. Any slider position above the device's real max produces
the same clamped hardware brightness, making it look like brightness
'caps' partway across the slider.

Pass the device's actual min/max from DisplayDeviceConfig so the slider
range matches what the hardware can actually do.

Change-Id: I35d450d4d67fc05f9701664c291cbeae6fc55f0d
---
 .../server/display/DisplayPowerController.java      | 13 +++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/services/core/java/com/android/server/display/DisplayPowerController.java b/services/core/java/com/android/server/display/DisplayPowerController.java
index bc99da745f11..e913ddbf50d0 100644
--- a/services/core/java/com/android/server/display/DisplayPowerController.java
+++ b/services/core/java/com/android/server/display/DisplayPowerController.java
@@ -2114,9 +2114,18 @@ final class DisplayPowerController implements AutomaticBrightnessController.Call
         final HighBrightnessModeData hbmData =
                 ddConfig != null ? ddConfig.getHighBrightnessModeData() : null;
         final DisplayDeviceInfo info = mDisplayDevice.getDisplayDeviceInfoLocked();
+        // Use the device's actual brightness range (from DisplayDeviceConfig) instead of the
+        // global PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MIN/MAX. Otherwise BrightnessRangeController reports
+        // the HBM max as 1.0, the QS slider thinks its range is 0-1.0, and any slider position
+        // above the device's real max produces the same hardware brightness — looking like the
+        // brightness "caps" partway across the slider.
+        final float deviceMin = ddConfig != null
+                ? ddConfig.getBrightnessMinimum() : PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MIN;
+        final float deviceMax = ddConfig != null
+                ? ddConfig.getBrightnessMaximum() : PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MAX;
         return mInjector.getHighBrightnessModeController(mHandler, info.width, info.height,
-                displayToken, displayUniqueId, PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MIN,
-                PowerManager.BRIGHTNESS_MAX, hbmData,
+                displayToken, displayUniqueId, deviceMin,
+                deviceMax, hbmData,
                 (sdrBrightness, maxDesiredHdrSdrRatio, ratioScaleFactor) ->
                         mDisplayDeviceConfig.getHdrBrightnessFromSdr(sdrBrightness,
                                 maxDesiredHdrSdrRatio, ratioScaleFactor), modeChangeCallback,
